"{\"uid\": \"si.com-college-mississippistate-all-things-state-nine-msu-athletes-and-coaches-competing-at-olympic-games-the-morning-bell-july-26-2024-01j3phdxjkt3\", \"text\": \"STARKVILLE \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Five former Mississippi State athletes and coaches have won Olympic medals and that number could rise by the time 2024 Summer Olympics in Paris have concluded.  Mississippi State has its best chance to add more Olympic medalists with nine former athletes and coaches competing in Paris, the most ever in the school\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s history. Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a breakdown of the nine former Mississippi State athletes competing in Paris:  Catalina Perez (Colombia) and Ilana Izquierdo (Colombia) are the first-ever Bulldogs to compete in Olympic soccer. Izquierdo also becomes MSU\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 11th athlete to compete in the Olympics while an active athlete for MSU (Note: Columbia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 team lost to France 3-2 on Thursday).  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Soccer:Colombia vs. New Zealand, 10 a.m. Sunday, Peacock  Nuno Borges (Portugal) is the first Bulldog ever to compete in men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s tennis and he does less than a week after defeating Rafael Nadal in straight sets on a clay court.  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Singles:Borges vs. Navone (Argentina), Saturday, Peacock  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Doubles:Portugal vs. Greece, Saturday, Peacock  Curtis Thompson (USA) is the only American-MSU athlete to compete in Paris this summer. This will be the second Olympic games appearance for MSU\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first-ever NCAA Champion in men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s javelin. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be joined by Anderson Peters (Grenada) in the javelin competition.  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Javelin:Qualifying Heats, 3:20 a.m. August 6  Marco Arop (Canada) and Navasky Anderson (Jamaica) will compete in the 800-meter run. This will be Arop\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s second-straight Olympics appearance and Anderson will be the first Jamaican man to race in the 800M at the Olympics in 16 years.  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 800M:First Round, 4:55 a.m. August 7  Lee Eppie (Botswana) and his 4x400-meter relay team hold the fastest time in the world by a national team this season. If they keep that streak going in Paris, Eppie could be one of four men to win Botswana\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first-ever Olympic medal.  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 4x400M Relay:First Round, 4:05 a.m. August 9  No games scheduled.  No games played.  38  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI am proud to say I had a bet with a guy from Chicago who said Chicago is windier and colder than Wyoming. Wyoming dominated them.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Award-winning sports editor, writer, columnist, and photographer with 15 years\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 experience offering his opinion and insight about the sports world in Mississippi and Texas, but he was taken to Razorback pep rallies at Billy Bob's Texas in Fort Worth before he could walk. Taylor has covered all levels of sports, from small high schools in the Mississippi Delta to NFL games. Follow Taylor on Twitter and Facebook.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"